<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-177-986  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 177 986.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Teleconnect  April 1989 v7 n4 p20(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Telecon Library Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Cabling checklist: Jim Morgan's 14 biggest mistakes to avoid.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Morgan, Jim.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Advice on telecommunications cabling is provided through thecorrection of 14 common mistakes in engineering perspective,planning or design.andP;  These mistakes include: thinking opticalfiber for workstations is at least five years away - it isavailable now; believing unshielded twisted pair can handle morethan 8M-bps to 10M-bps; not realizing that optical fiber isreplacing shielded twisted-pair; believing old cabling can bereused; thinking 64K-bps i high speed; and making telecom closetsless than 10 x 8 feet.andP;  Each mistake is resolved with a viable,future-oriented communications perspective or solution.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Topic:     System DesignSystem DevelopmentCommunications EquipmentCommunications ManagementCablesCommunications CircuitsTelephone Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>JIM MORGAN's 14 CABLING CHECKLISTandM;1.andP;  Thinking fiber to workstations is 5-10 years out.andP;  It's not.andP;  It's here.andO;It's already under way by leading users.andM;2.andP;  Listening to vendors who say &quot;You only need to install two pair for myPBX.&quot;andP;  Rubbish.andP;  Each workplace should have a minimum of eight pairs -- twosets of four pairs in two separate sheaths.andM;3.andP;  Keeping PBX and cabling in the same RFP.andP;  They're different.andP;  They mustbe separated and bid separately.andM;4.andP;  Thinking &quot;universal cabling&quot; is universal cabling.andP;  In addition to voiceand data, it also means video, HVAC, EMS (energy management) and security.andO;At an airport we identified 27 different types of signals.andP;  The ATandamp;T PDS, forexample, can only handle 24 signals.andP;  You can't use it for fire alarm andpublic address, for example.andP;  This is not an indictment of the ATandamp;T system.andO;It's good.andP;  But like everything, it has limitations.andM;5.andP;  Not understanding we are pushing The Laws of Physics on unshieldedtwisted pair.andP;  The limit is eight to 10 megabits per second.andP;  If you wanthigher, you must go to coax or fiber, preferably fiber.andM;6.andP;  Installing shielded twisted pair instead of fiber.andP;  Shielded twistedpair, like coaxial, is on the way out.andP;  Fiber is plummeting in price andcoming increasingly to the desktop.andM;7.andP;  Not watching the bend on fiber.andP;  You can't bend it as easily as cable.andO;Your curves have to be much broader.andP;  Terminating fiber is more difficultalso.andM;8.andP;  Making telecom closets less than 10 x 8 feet.andP;  This may be what Russiaallows for living space for one person.andP;  It's not enough for them and itsurely isn't enough for today's cable closets.andM;9.andP;  Thinking 64 Kbps as &quot;high speed.&quot;andP;  It soon will be medium speed.andM;10.andP;  Not planning for megabits per second to workstations over next three tofive years.andP;  There already are LANs -- local area networks delivering 80megabits per second transmission speed to the desktop.andP;  And that speed isneeded.andM;11.andP;  Re-using old installed &quot;rats' nest.&quot;andP;  The old stuff is simply not goodenough for today's and tomorrow's high-technology installation.andP;  Moreover,the old stuff is never sufficiently documented.andM;12.andP;  Making your cabling RFP fewer than dozen pages long.andP;  It's too complex.andO;You have to specify what you will be carrying, short-term, long-term, etc.andM;13.andP;  Buying cheap.andP;  You don't get enough of it.andP;  You get the wrong stuff.andO;Remember the classic cabling aphorism: &quot;You pay me now or you pay me later.andO;But you'll always pay me.&quot;andM;14.andP;  Not buying sophisticated cable engineering.andP;  What comes for &quot;free&quot; fromthe equipment vendors is usually worth what you pay for it.andP;  Equipmentvendors want to sell equipment cheap today, and moves and changes expensivetomorrow.andO;</TEXT></DOC>